description: Middle English notable, from Anglo-Norman notable, Middle French notable (“noteworthy”), from Latin notābilis (“noteworthy, extraordinary”), from notō (“to note, mark”); corresponding to note +‎ -able.

adjectives.description: notable (comparative more notable, superlative most notable)

entries.meaning: Worthy of note; remarkable; memorable; noted or distinguished. [from 14th c.]
examples: Synonyms: eminent, noteworthy; see also Thesaurus:notable

entries.meaning: Easily noted (without connotations of value); clearly noticeable, conspicuous. [from 14th c.]
examples: Synonyms: apparent, evident; see also Thesaurus:obvious

entries.meaning: That can be observed; perceptible. [from 14th c.]
(now rare) Industrious, energetic; (specifically) (usually of a woman) capable, efficient in household management. [from 17th c.]
A person or thing of distinction.
examples: What we ought to have, in my opinion, is a meeting of notables—men whose names will be of weight with the country and who can be depended upon to agree to an independent course.
